content.description: Climb the face and arete which is slightly overhanging and has some long reaches on it.
content.location: Face/Arete between "Last Hurrah" (to the left) and "Afternoon Delight" (to the left)

content.description: Start in "Last Hurrah" and move left into a jam crack. Ascend the jam crack as it goes up under the overhang that is part of "Do or Fly" which then works back right into "Last Hurrah" at the chock stone.
content.location: Start in "Last Hurrah" and move left after 15'

content.description: Approximately 50' to the left of the access gully are two significant rocks buldges with a crack separating them. These are the "cheeks"
content.location: This is the first major climbable feature from the access gully.

climbs.name: Trisha's Delima
climbs.fa: Lin Casciato, Mark Kerns, Richard Wilkins 1977

content.description: Follow the obvious crack and ledge system to the left of "Classic Crack" Mid way there is a semi detached flake where one stems to the right flake.
content.location: To the left of "Classic Crack" and the right of  'Sausalito"

content.description: Three short climbs (25') that are within 10' of each other and just to the right of the access trail. The left crack is 5.8+ finger crack, the middle is 5.6 off width open book, and right a 5.4 squeeze chimney.
content.location: Just to the right of the access trail through the cliff band

content.description: To the left of "Too Fat to Fly"  is a finger crack.  Climb the crack to the top.
content.location: To the left of "Too Fat to Fly"

content.description: To the left of "Can't Dance" is a 30' finger crack with horizontals ledges
content.location: To the left of "Can't Dance"

content.description: Proceed up an easy crack to a ledge. Face above may be climbed by any fair means either by climbing the face or the nose ot the left.
content.protection: Originally boldly lead on nuts but now bolted.
content.location: To left around from "Sausalito" on the face proper.

content.description:
Climb the bolted arete to the right of Spacey Face staying on the left side of the arete. 

  The name and the grade is simply a description as I am unsure if it was ever formally named by the FA party. I have also not climbed it so I am unsure of the exact grade - thus the old 5.9+ grade is used.
content.location: Start on the right side of the block at the base of the face.

content.description: Approximate 10' left of "Two Cheeks" is a wide chimney. Climb directly up this non-exposed route.
content.location: This is the second major climbable feature from the access gully.

content.description: Just left of the "Smoke Stack" on the rock nose is 50' left leaning crack. Face climb the bottom and jam the top which becomes an offwidth.
content.protection: Nuts and cams, large-ish for the top part.
content.location: This is the third major climbable feature from the access gully.

content.description: To the left of "Trisha'a Delima" is a broke ledge and crack system that leads to a ledge 1/2 up. Above the ledge is an overhanging face. Move left of the ledge utilizing an undercling. Finish out the climb via and airy nubbins and solution pockets.
content.location: To the left of "Trisha'a Delima"

content.description: Pesky Rodent has two starts one beginning just to the left of "Dusty Devil' or directly beneath the main crack. The first start involves going up a thin crack that traverse left into the main crack. The second start goes directly up to the main crack. Both end on a small ledge. Proceed up the off-width crack.
content.location: To the left of "Dusty Devil"

content.description:
The final climb in this group. And easy scramble up to a wide chimney.  

  NOTE: Good views of "Do or Fly" and "Last Hurrah" is possible from half way up.
content.location: To the left of "Do or Fly"

content.description:
To the left of "Afternoon Delight" is a very deep crack that is slightly over hanging from top to bottom. Ascend the crack.  

  NOTE: a large chock stone is found at the top that is holding back several other large blocks.
content.protection: Medium to large nuts and cams.
content.location: To the left of "Afternoon Delight"

content.description: Climb the face using the natural pro with the exception of two bolts. The upper face has thin cracks that take gear.
content.protection: Small nuts and cams w/a couple of draws for two bolts.
content.location: The face between Dusty Devil (to the right) and Pesty Rodent (to the left).

content.description: Arete to the right of Shit Eye. Start on Shit Eye and move right.
content.location: Arete to the right of Shit Eye, left of the Chimney Face Left

content.description: Climb a steep face to the right of "Classic Crack"

Dusty Devil is an excellent example of the deep offwidths cracks at High Valley. It is further complicated by having two slightly overhanging sections. Begin directly up the crack to the first overhang which leads to a small ledge. The second section is similar crack leading to a slight overhang but the walls are smooth.
content.location: To the left of "Spacy Face"

climbs.name: Do or Fly
climbs.fa: Lin Casciato, Mark Kerns, Richard Wilkins 1977

content.description: This is the classic High Valley route. Ascend up a beautiful fist jam crack. The crux is at the top where it overhangs.
content.location: To the left of "Unnamed Symphony"

climbs.name: Classic Crack
climbs.fa: Lin Casciato, Mark Kerns, Richard Wilkins 1977

content.description: The obvious dihedral to the left of Smokestack. The rating is based on staying in the crack and not using "Trisha's Dilema" The crack can be stemmed or lay backed.
content.location: Dihedral to the left of Smoke Stack.

content.description: Overhanging face to the left of Smoke Stack
content.location: Overhanging face to the left of Smoke Stack

content.description: The overhanging face to the right Smoke Stack.
content.location: The overhanging face to the right Smoke Stack.

content.description: The  farthest climb to the right begins below a roof and goes up a wide chimney to the roof. Traverse right onto the face and move up to the top of the roof.
content.location: Far left of "Old Bologna" and the southern scramble route to the cliff top are three climbs identified from the road by a very obvious crack.

content.description: Ascend a beautiful sicle crack up a small face. Follow the crack completely to the left or directly up the face as the crack thins. Either ends on a large ledge, proceed up another off-width crackto the top.
content.location: To the left "Pesky Rodent"

content.description: The upper wall that is about 300 feet above the road. Sunny in the mornings and shady in the afternoons. Routes are listed by features from right to left.
